Cool survey!

I do believe that there are forces that cannot be explained by modern science. Just because science cannot explain them doesn't mean that this is "God" though.

I feel like "God" is the fallback answer for humans, as far back as time has been recorded, for when we can't figure things out. It's the easy answer when we grasp at straws, or really have no way of figuring things out.

I believe that there is no afterlife, and once you die its game over. Just like how you know nothing about your "previous life". The human mind wants to draw connections, even in places where it's inappropriate or no logical connection can be drawn.

Life is random. Life is precious. Make the most out of the short time you have on Earth. Some people get lucky, some don't... and it has nothing to do with whether you are a good person or not.

Lastly, if there IS a god or godlike force... and I'm totally wrong... I have issues believing that individual people can connect with this god, or that he/she/it is even concerned with the day to day life of people.

Many of the questions were meaningless from a Buddhist point of view.

Beings are not separate unchanging entities. If my idea of myself is an illusion and violates logic, why would it make sense to project the existence of a big invisible ego in the sky? (God)

Cause & Effect simply dictates there are consequences from your current behavior. Next life, or current life (the distinction of which is a lot less clear if I'm a different person from what I was when I was 1.) Unrighteous? More like "things that cause this kind of effect cause this kind of effect which we don't like". Hitting the wall with your head causes suffering. Being mean to someone causes suffering. Etc.

Nirvana doesn't mean what you think it means.

"Holy Scriptures?" Buddhism provides maps of your experience, just as Science provides maps of the behavior of the world. So yes they're practical guides, but while precious they're not "holy".

I don't know what you mean by the first question. Science will continue to learn about phenomena we don't know much about. It's not "done". There are things we cannot explain or replicate such as consciousness. Will that always be the case? Is that supernatural, or by "supernatural" the irrational process of assigning an untestable cause to a phenomenon and deciding we're done?

Such a survey should ask questions whose answers would indicate whether the respondent holds values that are commonly attributed to religion, yet also indicate their morality.
